# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: circuit-complexity
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:circuit-complexity/ac0] Integer addition and subtraction are computable in AC0, but multiplication is not (specifically, when the inputs are two integers under the usual binary or base-10 representations of integers).
[src:circuit-complexity/ac0] Since it is a circuit class, like P/poly, AC0 also contains every unary language.
[src:circuit-complexity/ac0] From a descriptive complexity viewpoint, DLOGTIME-uniform AC0 is equal to the descriptive class FO+BIT of all languages describable in first-order logic with the addition of the BIT predicate, or alternatively by FO(+, ×), or by Turing machine in the logarithmic hierarchy.
[src:circuit-complexity/ac0] In 1984 Furst, Saxe, and Sipser showed that calculating the PARITY of the input bits (unlike the aforementioned addition/subtraction problems above which had two inputs) cannot be decided by any AC0 circuits, even with non-uniformity.
[src:circuit-complexity/ac0] Similarly, computing the majority is also not in ${\mathsf {AC}}^{0}$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/ac0] It follows that AC0 is strictly smaller than TC0.
[src:circuit-complexity/ac0] Note that "PARITY" is also called "XOR" in the literature.
[src:circuit-complexity/ac0] However, PARITY is only barely out of AC0, in the sense that for any $k>0$ , there exists a family of alternating circuits using depth $\lceil k\ln n/\ln \ln n\rceil$ and size $O\left(2^{(\ln n)^{1/k}}{\frac {n}{(\ln n)^{1/k}}}\right)$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/ac0] In particular, setting k to be a large constant, then there exists a family of alternating circuits using depth $O(\ln n/\ln \ln n)\ll O(\ln n)$ , and size only slightly superlinear.
[src:circuit-complexity/ac0] ${\mathsf {AC}}^{0}$ can be divided further, into a hierarchy of languages requiring up to 1 layer, 2 layers, etc.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] In computational complexity theory and circuit complexity, a **Boolean circuit** is a mathematical model for combinational digital logic circuits.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] A formal language can be decided by a family of Boolean circuits, one circuit for each possible input length.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] Boolean circuits are defined in terms of the logic gates they contain.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] For example, a circuit might contain binary AND and OR gates and unary NOT gates, or be entirely described by binary NAND gates.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] Each gate corresponds to some Boolean function that takes a fixed number of bits as input and outputs a single bit.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] Boolean circuits provide a model for many digital components used in computer engineering, including multiplexers, adders, and arithmetic logic units, but they exclude sequential logic.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] They are an abstraction that omits many aspects relevant to designing real digital logic circuits, such as metastability, fanout, glitches, power consumption, and propagation delay variability.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] In giving a formal definition of Boolean circuits, Vollmer starts by defining a basis as set *B* of Boolean functions, corresponding to the gates allowable in the circuit model.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] A Boolean circuit over a basis *B*, with *n* inputs and *m* outputs, is then defined as a finite directed acyclic graph.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] Each vertex corresponds to either a basis function or one of the inputs, and there is a set of exactly *m* nodes which are labeled as the outputs.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] The edges must also have some ordering, to distinguish between different arguments to the same Boolean function.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] As a special case, a propositional formula or Boolean expression is a Boolean circuit with a single output node in which every other node has fan-out of 1.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] Thus, a Boolean circuit can be regarded as a generalization that allows shared subformulas and multiple outputs.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] A common basis for Boolean circuits is the set {AND, OR, NOT}, which is functionally complete, i.e. from which all other Boolean functions can be constructed.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] A particular circuit acts only on inputs of fixed size.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] However, formal languages (the string-based representations of decision problems) contain strings of different lengths, so languages cannot be fully captured by a single circuit (in contrast to the Turing machine model, in which a language is fully described by a single Turing machine).
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] A language is instead represented by a *circuit family*.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] A circuit family is an infinite list of circuits $(C_{0},C_{1},C_{2},...)$ , where $C_{n}$ has n input variables.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] A circuit family is said to decide a language L if, for every string w , w is in the language L if and only if $C_{n}(w)=1$ , where n is the length of w .
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] In other words, a language is the set of strings which, when applied to the circuits corresponding to their lengths, evaluate to 1.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] Several important complexity measures can be defined on Boolean circuits, including circuit depth, circuit size, and the number of alternations between AND gates and OR gates.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] For example, the size complexity of a Boolean circuit is the number of gates in the circuit.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] There is a natural connection between circuit size complexity and time complexity.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] Intuitively, a language with small time complexity (that is, requires relatively few sequential operations on a Turing machine), also has a small circuit complexity (that is, requires relatively few Boolean operations).
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] Formally, it can be shown that if a language is in ${\mathsf {TIME}}(t(n))$ , where t is a function $t:\mathbb {N} \to \mathbb {N}$ , then it has circuit size complexity $O(t^{2}(n))$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] Several important complexity classes are defined in terms of Boolean circuits.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] The most general of these is P/poly, the set of languages that are decidable by polynomial-size circuit families.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] It follows directly from the fact that languages in ${\mathsf {TIME}}(t(n))$ have circuit complexity $O(t^{2}(n))$ that P $\subseteq$ P/poly.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] In other words, any problem that can be computed in polynomial time by a deterministic Turing machine can also be computed by a polynomial-size circuit family.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] It is further the case that the inclusion is proper (i.e.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] P $\subsetneq$ P/poly) because there are undecidable problems that are in P/poly.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] P/poly turns out to have a number of properties that make it highly useful in the study of the relationships between complexity classes.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] In particular, it is helpful in investigating problems related to P versus NP.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] For example, if there is any language in NP that is not in P/poly then P $\neq$ NP.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] P/poly also helps to investigate properties of the polynomial hierarchy.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] For example, if NP ⊆ P/poly, then PH collapses to $\Sigma _{2}^{\mathsf {P}}$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] A full description of the relations between P/poly and other complexity classes is available at "Importance of P/poly".
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] P/poly also has the interesting feature that it can be equivalently defined as the class of languages recognized by a polynomial-time Turing machine with a polynomial-bounded advice function.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] Two subclasses of P/poly that have interesting properties in their own right are NC and AC.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] These classes are defined not only in terms of their circuit size but also in terms of their *depth*.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] The depth of a circuit is the length of the longest directed path from an input node to the output node.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] The class NC is the set of languages that can be solved by circuit families that are restricted not only to having polynomial-size but also to having polylogarithmic depth.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] The class AC is defined similarly to NC, however gates are allowed to have unbounded fan-in (that is, the AND and OR gates can be applied to more than two bits).
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] NC is an important class because it turns out that it represents the class of languages that have efficient parallel algorithms.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] The circuit value problem — the problem of computing the output of a given Boolean circuit on a given input string — is a P-complete decision problem.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] Therefore, this problem is considered to be "inherently sequential" in the sense that there is likely no efficient, highly parallel algorithm that solves the problem.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] Logic circuits are physical representation of simple logic operations, AND, OR and NOT (and their combinations, such as non-sequential flip-flops or circuit networks), that form a mathematical structure known as Boolean algebra.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] They are complete in sense that they can perform any deterministic algorithm.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] However, it just happens that this is not all there is.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] In the physical world we also encounter randomness, notable in small systems governed by quantization effects, which is described by theory of quantum mechanics.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] Logic circuits cannot produce any randomness, and in that sense they form an incomplete logic set.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] Remedy to that is found in adding an ad-hoc random bit generator to logic networks, or computers, such as in probabilistic Turing machine.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] A recent work has introduced a theoretical concept of an inherently random logic circuit named *random flip-flop*, which completes the set.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] It conveniently packs randomness and is inter-operable with deterministic Boolean logic circuits.
[src:circuit-complexity/boolean-circuit] However, an algebraic structure equivalent of Boolean algebra and associated methods of circuit construction and reduction for the extended set is yet unknown.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] In theoretical computer science, **circuit complexity** is a branch of computational complexity theory in which Boolean functions are classified according to the size or depth of the Boolean circuits that compute them.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] A related notion is the circuit complexity of a recursive language that is decided by a **uniform** family of circuits $C_{1},C_{2},\ldots$ (see below).
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] Proving lower bounds on size of Boolean circuits computing explicit Boolean functions is a popular approach to separating complexity classes.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] For example, a prominent circuit class P/poly consists of Boolean functions computable by circuits of polynomial size.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] Proving that ${\mathsf {NP}}\not \subseteq {\mathsf {P/poly}}$ would separate P and NP (see below).
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] Complexity classes defined in terms of Boolean circuits include AC0, AC, TC0, NC1, NC, and P/poly.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] A Boolean circuit with n input bits is a directed acyclic graph in which every node (usually called *gates* in this context) is either an input node of in-degree 0 labelled by one of the n input bits, an AND gate, an OR gate, or a NOT gate.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] One of these gates is designated as the output gate.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] Such a circuit naturally computes a function of its n inputs.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] The **size** of a circuit is the number of gates it contains and its **depth** is the maximal length of a path from an input gate to the output gate.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] There are two major notions of circuit complexity.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] The **circuit-size complexity** of a Boolean function f is the minimal size of any circuit computing f .
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] The **circuit-depth complexity** of a Boolean function f is the minimal depth of any circuit computing f .
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] These notions generalize when one considers the circuit complexity of any formal language that contains strings with different bit lengths, especially infinite languages.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] Boolean circuits, however, only allow a fixed number of input bits.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] Thus, no single Boolean circuit is capable of deciding such a language.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] To account for this possibility, one considers families of circuits $C_{1},C_{2},\ldots$ where each $C_{n}$ accepts inputs of size n .
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] Each circuit family will naturally generate the language by circuit $C_{n}$ outputting 1 when a length n string is a member of the family, and 0 otherwise.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] We say that a family of circuits is **size minimal** if there is no other family that decides on inputs of any size, n , with a circuit of smaller size than $C_{n}$ (respectively for **depth minimal** families).
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] Thus, circuit complexity is meaningful even for non-recursive languages.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] The notion of a **uniform family** enables variants of circuit complexity to be related to algorithm-based complexity measures of recursive languages.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] However, the non-uniform variant is helpful to find lower bounds on how complex any circuit family must be in order to decide given languages.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] Hence, the **circuit-size complexity** of a formal language A is defined as the function $t:\mathbb {N} \to \mathbb {N}$ , that relates a bit length of an input, n , to the circuit-size complexity of a minimal circuit $C_{n}$ that decides whether inputs of that length are in A .
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] The **circuit-depth complexity** is defined similarly.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] An individual computational problem is thus associated with a particular *family* of Boolean circuits $C_{1},C_{2},\dots$ where each $C_{n}$ is the circuit handling inputs of *n* bits.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] A *uniformity* condition is often imposed on these families, requiring the existence of some possibly resource-bounded Turing machine that, on input *n*, produces a description of the individual circuit $C_{n}$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] When this Turing machine has a running time polynomial in *n*, the circuit family is said to be P-uniform.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] The stricter requirement of DLOGTIME-uniformity is of particular interest in the study of shallow-depth circuit-classes such as AC0 or TC0.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] When no resource bounds are specified, a language is recursive (i.e., decidable by a Turing machine) if and only if the language is decided by a uniform family of Boolean circuits.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] Circuit complexity goes back to Shannon in 1949, who proved that almost all Boolean functions on *n* variables require circuits of size Θ(2*n*/*n*).
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] Despite this fact, complexity theorists have so far been unable to prove a superlinear lower bound for any explicit function.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] Superpolynomial lower bounds have been proved under certain restrictions on the family of circuits used.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] The first function for which superpolynomial circuit lower bounds were shown was the parity function, which computes the sum of its input bits modulo 2.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] The fact that parity is not contained in AC0 was first established independently by Ajtai in 1983 and by Furst, Saxe and Sipser in 1984.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] Later improvements by Håstad in 1987 established that any family of constant-depth circuits computing the parity function requires exponential size.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] Extending a result of Razborov, Smolensky in 1987 proved that this is true even if the circuit is augmented with gates computing the sum of its input bits modulo some odd prime *p*.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] The *k*-clique problem is to decide whether a given graph on *n* vertices has a clique of size *k*.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] For any particular choice of the constants *n* and *k*, the graph can be encoded in binary using ${n \choose 2}$ bits, which indicate for each possible edge whether it is present.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] Then the *k*-clique problem is formalized as a function $f_{k}:\{0,1\}^{n \choose 2}\to \{0,1\}$ such that $f_{k}$ outputs 1 if and only if the graph encoded by the string contains a clique of size *k*.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] This family of functions is monotone and can be computed by a family of circuits, but it has been shown that it cannot be computed by a polynomial-size family of monotone circuits (that is, circuits with AND and OR gates but without negation).
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] The original result of Razborov in 1985 was later improved to an exponential-size lower bound by Alon and Boppana in 1987.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] In 2008, Rossman showed that constant-depth circuits with AND, OR, and NOT gates require size $\Omega (n^{k/4})$ to solve the *k*-clique problem even in the average case.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] Moreover, there is a circuit of size $n^{k/4+O(1)}$ that computes $f_{k}$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] In 1999, Raz and McKenzie later showed that the monotone NC hierarchy is infinite.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] The integer division problem lies in uniform TC0.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] Circuit lower bounds are generally difficult.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] It is open whether NEXPTIME has nonuniform TC0 circuits.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] Proofs of circuit lower bounds are strongly connected to derandomization.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] A proof that ${\mathsf {P}}={\mathsf {BPP}}$ would imply that either ${\mathsf {NEXP}}\not \subseteq {\mathsf {P/poly}}$ or that the permanent of a matrix cannot be computed by nonuniform arithmetic circuits (polynomials) of polynomial size and polynomial degree.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] In 1997, Razborov and Rudich showed that many known circuit lower bounds for explicit Boolean functions imply the existence of so called natural properties useful against the respective circuit class.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] On the other hand, natural properties useful against P/poly would break strong pseudorandom generators.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] This is often interpreted as a "natural proofs" barrier for proving strong circuit lower bounds.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] In 2016, Carmosino, Impagliazzo, Kabanets and Kolokolova proved that natural properties can be also used to construct efficient learning algorithms.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] Many circuit complexity classes are defined in terms of class hierarchies.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] For each non-negative integer *i*, there is a class NCi, consisting of polynomial-size circuits of depth $O(\log ^{i}(n))$ , using bounded fan-in AND, OR, and NOT gates.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] The union NC of all of these classes is a subject of study.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] By considering unbounded fan-in gates, the classes ACi and AC (which is equal to NC) can be constructed.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] Many other circuit complexity classes with the same size and depth restrictions can be constructed by allowing different sets of gates.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] If a certain language, A , belongs to the time-complexity class ${\text{TIME}}(t(n))$ for some function $t:\mathbb {N} \to \mathbb {N}$ , then A has circuit complexity ${\mathcal {O}}(t(n)\log t(n))$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] If the Turing Machine that accepts the language is oblivious (meaning that it reads and writes the same memory cells regardless of input), then A has circuit complexity ${\mathcal {O}}(t(n))$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] A monotone Boolean circuit is one that has only AND and OR gates, but no NOT gates.
[src:circuit-complexity/circuit-complexity] A monotone circuit can only compute a monotone Boolean function, which is a function $f:\{0,1\}^{n}\to \{0,1\}$ where for every $x,y\in \{0,1\}^{n}$ , $x\leq y\implies f(x)\leq f(y)$ , where $x\leq y$ means that $x_{i}\leq y_{i}$ for all $i\in \{1,\ldots ,n\}$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/natural-proof] In computational complexity theory, a **natural proof** is a certain kind of proof establishing that one complexity class differs from another one.
[src:circuit-complexity/natural-proof] While these proofs are in some sense "natural", it can be shown (assuming a widely believed conjecture on the existence of pseudorandom functions) that no such proof can possibly be used to solve the P vs.
[src:circuit-complexity/natural-proof] The notion of natural proofs was introduced by Alexander Razborov and Steven Rudich in their article "Natural Proofs", first presented in 1994, and later published in 1997, for which they received the 2007 Gödel Prize.
[src:circuit-complexity/natural-proof] Specifically, natural proofs prove lower bounds on the circuit complexity of boolean functions.
[src:circuit-complexity/natural-proof] A natural proof shows, either directly or indirectly, that a boolean function has a certain **natural combinatorial property**.
[src:circuit-complexity/natural-proof] Under the assumption that pseudorandom functions exist with "exponential hardness" as specified in their main theorem, Razborov and Rudich show that these proofs cannot separate certain complexity classes.
[src:circuit-complexity/natural-proof] Notably, assuming pseudorandom functions exist, these proofs cannot separate the complexity classes P and NP.
[src:circuit-complexity/natural-proof] no proof strategy along these lines can ever succeed.
[src:circuit-complexity/natural-proof] A property of boolean functions is defined to be *natural* if it contains a property meeting the constructivity and largeness conditions defined by Razborov and Rudich.
[src:circuit-complexity/natural-proof] Roughly speaking, the constructivity condition requires that a property be decidable in (quasi-)polynomial time when the 2*n*-sized truth table of an *n*-input boolean function is given as input, asymptotically as *n* increases.
[src:circuit-complexity/natural-proof] This is the same as time singly exponential in *n*.
[src:circuit-complexity/natural-proof] Properties that are easy to understand are likely to satisfy this condition.
[src:circuit-complexity/natural-proof] The largeness condition requires that the property hold for a sufficiently large fraction of the set of all boolean functions.
[src:circuit-complexity/natural-proof] A property is *useful* against a complexity class *C* if every sequence of boolean functions having the property infinitely often defines a language outside of *C*.
[src:circuit-complexity/natural-proof] A *natural proof* is a proof that establishes that a certain language lies outside of *C* and refers to a natural property that is useful against *C*.
[src:circuit-complexity/natural-proof] Razborov and Rudich give a number of examples of lower-bound proofs against classes *C* smaller than P/poly that can be "naturalized", i.e. converted into natural proofs.
[src:circuit-complexity/natural-proof] An important example treats proofs that the parity problem is not in the class AC0.
[src:circuit-complexity/natural-proof] They give strong evidence that the techniques used in these proofs cannot be extended to show stronger lower bounds.
[src:circuit-complexity/natural-proof] In particular, AC0-natural proofs cannot be useful against AC0[m].
[src:circuit-complexity/natural-proof] Razborov and Rudich also reproduce Avi Wigderson's unconditional proof that natural proofs cannot prove exponential lower bounds for the discrete logarithm problem.
[src:circuit-complexity/natural-proof] There is strong current belief that the mechanism of this paper actually blocks lower-bound proofs against the complexity class TC0 of constant-depth, polynomial-sized threshold circuits, which is believed but not proven smaller than P/poly.
[src:circuit-complexity/natural-proof] This belief is because, under widely believed conjectures regarding the hardness of factoring in certain elliptic curve groups, there exist exponentially hard pseudorandom functions computable in TC0.
[src:circuit-complexity/natural-proof] However, some researchers believe that the Razborov–Rudich limitations are actually good guidance for what a "super-natural" lower-bound proof might involve, such as properties hard or complete for exponential space.
[src:circuit-complexity/parity-function] In Boolean algebra, a **parity function** is a Boolean function whose value is one if and only if the input vector has an odd number of ones.
[src:circuit-complexity/parity-function] The parity function of two inputs is also known as the XOR function.
[src:circuit-complexity/parity-function] The parity function is notable for its role in theoretical investigation of circuit complexity of Boolean functions.
[src:circuit-complexity/parity-function] The output of the parity function is the parity bit.
[src:circuit-complexity/parity-function] The n -variable parity function is the Boolean function $f:\{0,1\}^{n}\to \{0,1\}$ with the property that $f(x)=1$ if and only if the number of ones in the vector $x\in \{0,1\}^{n}$ is odd.
[src:circuit-complexity/parity-function] Parity only depends on the number of ones and is therefore a symmetric Boolean function.
[src:circuit-complexity/parity-function] The *n*-variable parity function and its negation are the only Boolean functions for which all disjunctive normal forms have the maximal number of 2 *n* − 1 monomials of length *n* and all conjunctive normal forms have the maximal number of 2 *n* − 1 clauses of length *n*.
[src:circuit-complexity/parity-function] Some of the earliest work in computational complexity was 1961 bound of Bella Subbotovskaya showing the size of a Boolean formula computing parity must be at least $\Omega (n^{3/2})$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/parity-function] This work uses the method of random restrictions.
[src:circuit-complexity/parity-function] This exponent of $3/2$ has been increased through careful analysis to $1.63$ by Paterson and Zwick (1993) and then to 2 by Håstad (1998).
[src:circuit-complexity/parity-function] Similar results were also established for the majority, multiplication and transitive closure functions, by reduction from the parity function.
[src:circuit-complexity/parity-function] Håstad (1987) established tight exponential lower bounds on the size of constant-depth Boolean circuits for the parity function.
[src:circuit-complexity/parity-function] Håstad's Switching Lemma is the key technical tool used for these lower bounds and Johan Håstad was awarded the Gödel Prize for this work in 1994.
[src:circuit-complexity/parity-function] The precise result is that depth-k circuits with AND, OR, and NOT gates require size $\exp(\Omega (n^{\frac {1}{k-1}}))$ to compute the parity function.
[src:circuit-complexity/parity-function] This is asymptotically almost optimal as there are depth-k circuits computing parity which have size $\exp(O(n^{\frac {1}{k-1}})t)$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/parity-function] Assuming axiom of choice it can be proved that parity functions exist and there are $2^{2^{\aleph _{0}}}$ many of them; as many as the number of all functions from $\{0,1\}^{\omega }$ to $\{0,1\}$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/parity-function] It is enough to take one representative per equivalence class of relation $\approx$ defined as follows: $w\approx v$ if w and v differ at finite number of coordinates.
[src:circuit-complexity/parity-function] Having such representatives, we can map all of them to 0 ; the rest of f values are deducted unambiguously.
[src:circuit-complexity/parity-function] Another construction of an infinite parity function can be done using a non-principal ultrafilter U on $\omega$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/parity-function] The existence of non-principal ultrafilters on $\omega$ follows from – and is strictly weaker than – the axiom of choice.
[src:circuit-complexity/parity-function] The infinite parity function f is defined by mapping w to 0 if and only if $A_{w}$ is an element of the ultrafilter.
[src:circuit-complexity/parity-function] It is necessary to assume at least some amount of choice to prove that infinite parity functions exist.
[src:circuit-complexity/parity-function] If f is an infinite parity function and we consider the inverse image $f^{-1}[0]$ as a subset of the Cantor space $\{0,1\}^{\omega }$ , then $f^{-1}[0]$ is a non-measurable set and does not have the property of Baire.
[src:circuit-complexity/parity-function] Without the axiom of choice, it is consistent (relative to ZF) that all subsets of the Cantor space are measurable and have the property of Baire and thus that no infinite parity function exists; this holds in the Solovay model, for instance.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] In theoretical computer science, and specifically computational complexity theory and circuit complexity, **TC0** (Threshold Circuit) is the first class in the hierarchy of TC classes.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] TC0 contains all languages which are decided by Boolean circuits with constant depth and polynomial size, containing only unbounded fan-in AND gates, OR gates, NOT gates, and MAJ gates, or equivalently, threshold gates.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] TC0 contains several important problems, such as sorting *n* *n*-bit numbers, multiplying two *n*-bit numbers, integer division or recognizing the Dyck language with multiple types of parentheses.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] It is commonly used to model the computational complexity of bounded-depth neural networks, and indeed, it was originally proposed for this purpose.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] A **Boolean circuit family** is a sequence of Boolean circuits $C_{1},C_{2},C_{3},\dots$ consisting of a feedforward network of Boolean functions.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] Equivalently, instead of majority gates, we can use threshold gates with integer weights and thresholds, bounded by a polynomial.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] A threshold gate with k inputs is defined by a list of weights $w_{1},\dots ,w_{k}$ and a single threshold $\theta$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] A threshold gate is also called an artificial neuron.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] In this article, we by default consider Boolean circuits with a polynomial number of AND, OR, NOT, and threshold gates, with polynomial bound on integer weights and thresholds.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] The polynomial bound on weights and thresholds can be relaxed without changing the class ${\mathsf {TC}}^{0}$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] Whether ${\mathsf {TC}}^{0}\subseteq {\mathsf {NC}}^{1}$ is a strict inclusion is "one of the main open problems in circuit complexity".
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] In fact, it is even open whether ${\mathsf {TC}}^{0}\subseteq {\mathsf {P/poly}}$ is a strict inclusion!
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] More generally, randomness and hardness for have been shown to be closely related.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] It is also an open question whether ${\mathsf {NEXP}}\subseteq {\mathsf {TC}}^{0}$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] Note that because non-uniform ${\mathsf {TC}}^{0}$ and ${\mathsf {ACC}}^{0}$ can compute functions that are not Turing-computable, it is certainly the case that ${\mathsf {TC}}^{0}\not \subseteq {\mathsf {NEXP}}$ and ${\mathsf {ACC}}^{0}\not \subseteq {\mathsf {NEXP}}$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] The 2011 result simply shows that ${\mathsf {ACC}}^{0}$ and ${\mathsf {NEXP}}$ are incomparable classes.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] The open question is whether ${\mathsf {TC}}^{0}$ and ${\mathsf {NEXP}}$ are incomparable as well.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] Note that, while the nondeterministic time hierarchy theorem proves that ${\mathsf {NP}}\subsetneq {\mathsf {NEXP}}$ , both complexity classes are *uniform*, meaning that a single Turing machine is responsible for solving the problem at any input length.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] It has been proven that if ${\mathsf {TC}}^{0}={\mathsf {NC}}^{1}$ , then any $\epsilon >0$ , there exists a ${\mathsf {TC}}^{0}$ circuit family of gate number $O(n^{1+\epsilon })$ that solves the Boolean Formula Evaluation problem.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] Thus, any superlinear bound suffices to prove ${\mathsf {TC}}^{0}\neq {\mathsf {NC}}^{1}$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] DLOGTIME-uniform ${\mathsf {TC}}^{0}$ is also known as ${\mathsf {FOM}}$ , because it is equivalent to first-order logic with Majority quantifiers.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] It is usually considered the appropriate level of uniformity for ${\mathsf {TC}}^{0}$ , neither too strong nor too weak.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] Specifically, because P is usually suspected to be stronger than ${\mathsf {TC}}^{0}$ , while DLOGTIME is suspected to be equivalent in strength in some sense, DLOGTIME-uniformity is usually assumed, when uniformity is considered for ${\mathsf {TC}}^{0}$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] The permanent of a 0-1 matrix is not in uniform ${\mathsf {TC}}^{0}$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] By functional version one means the set of all functions $f(x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n})$ over non-negative integers that are bounded by functions of FP and $(y{\text{-th bit of }}f(x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}))$ is in the uniform TC0.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] TC0 can be divided further, into a hierarchy of languages requiring up to 1 layer, 2 layers, etc.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] The MAJ gate is sometimes called an **unweighted** threshold gate.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] They are equivalent up to a uniform polynomial overhead.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] Furthermore, there is an explicit algorithm, by which, given a single n -input threshold gate with arbitrary (unbounded) integer weights and thresholds, it constructs a depth-2 circuit using ${\mathsf {poly}}(n)$ -many AND, OR, NOT, and MAJ gates.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] Thus, any polynomial-size, depth- d threshold circuit can be simulated uniformly by a polynomial-size majority circuit of depth $d+1$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] As a separation theorem, it is known that the n -input Boolean inner product function (IP), defined below, is computable by a majority circuit with 3 layers and $O(n)$ gates, but is not computable by a threshold circuit with 2 layers and ${\mathsf {poly}}(n)$ gates.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] For any fixed n , because there are only finitely many Boolean functions that can be computed by a threshold logic unit, it is possible to set all $w_{1},\dots ,w_{n},\theta$ to be integers.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] Let $W(n)$ be the smallest number W such that every possible real threshold function of n variables can be realized using integer weights of absolute value $\leq W$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] Sometimes the class of polynomial-bounded weights and thresholds with depth d is denoted as ${\widehat {\mathsf {LT}}}_{d}:={\mathsf {TC}}_{d}^{0}$ , and ${\mathsf {LT}}_{d}$ denotes the class where the weight and thresholds are unbounded ("large weight threshold circuit").
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] This formalizes neural networks with real-valued activation functions.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] As previously stated, any polynomial-size, depth- d threshold circuit can be simulated uniformly by a polynomial-size majority circuit of depth $d+1$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] Allowing the sigmoid activation function $\sigma$ does not increase the power, that is, ${\mathsf {TC}}_{d}^{0}={\mathsf {TC}}_{d}^{0}(\sigma )$ for all $d\geq 1$ , assuming the weights are polynomially bounded.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] Like how the P class has a probabilistic version BPP, the ${\mathsf {TC}}^{0}$ has a probabilistic version ${\mathsf {RTC}}^{0}$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] It is defined as the class of languages that can be polynomial-probabilistically decided.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] Let $C_{1},C_{2},C_{3},\dots$ be a Boolean circuit family that takes two kinds of inputs.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] A given circuit $C_{n}$ takes the deterministic inputs $x_{1},\dots ,x_{n}$ , and the random inputs $y_{1},\dots ,y_{m}$ , where $m={\mathsf {poly}}(n)$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] The random inputs are sampled uniformly over all $2^{m}$ possibilities.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] Similarly, (feedforward) Boltzmann machines have been modelled as ${\mathsf {RTC}}^{0}$ circuits with boundedly-unreliable threshold units.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] That is, each threshold unit may, independently at random, with a bounded probability $\epsilon <1/2$ , make the wrong output.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] Sometimes, this class is also called ${\mathsf {BPTC}}^{0}$ , in a closer analogy with BPP.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] By the standard trick of sampling many times then taking the majority opinion, any d -layer ${\mathsf {RTC}}^{0}$ circuit can be converted to a $(d+1)$ -layer ${\mathsf {BPTC}}^{0}$ circuit.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] That at least one advice exists is proven by Hoeffding's inequality, with essentially the same argument as the median trick.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] This argument is merely an existence proof, and thus not uniform in a way that matters for ${\mathsf {TC}}^{0}$ , since it gives no algorithm for discovering the advice other than brute-force enumeration.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] Let $\oplus$ be defined as the parity function, or the XOR function.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] It is an open question how many levels the hierarchy has.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] It is also an open question whether the hierarchy collapses, that is, ${\mathsf {TC}}^{0}={\mathsf {TC}}_{3}^{0}$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] In fact, there is still no exponential lower bound for ${\mathsf {LT}}_{2}^{0}$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] Therefore, *a fortiori*, there is still no exponential lower bound for depth-3 polynomial-size majority circuits.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] There are exponential lower bounds if further restrictions are imposed on layer 1, such as requiring it to only contain AND gates, or only bounded fan-in gates.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] The hierarchy for *monotone* ${\mathsf {TC}}^{0}$ (that is, ${\mathsf {TC}}^{0}$ without Boolean negations) is strongly separated.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] Specifically, for each d , there has been constructed a language that is decidable by a depth d circuit family using only $O(n)$ AND and OR gates, but requires exponential size to compute by a monotone ${\mathsf {TC}}_{d-1}^{0}$ .
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] If the polynomial bound on the number of gates is relaxed, then ${\mathsf {TC}}_{3}^{0}$ is quite powerful.
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] Specifically, any language in ${\mathsf {ACC}}^{0}$ can be decided by a circuit family in ${\mathsf {TC}}_{3}^{0}$ (using Majority gates), except that it uses a quasi-polynomial number of gates (instead of polynomial).
[src:circuit-complexity/tc0] This result is optimal, in that there exists a function that is computable with 3 layers of ${\mathsf {AC}}^{0}$ , but requires at least an exponential number of gates for ${\mathsf {TC}}_{2}^{0}$ (using Majority gates).
